{"/service/ndnp/njr/batch_njr_irene_ver02/data/sn90063041/0033289707A/1920061101/0463.xml":{"full_text":"VOLUME 31, NO. 1\nWILDWOOD, NEW JERSEY, FRIDAY, JUNE 11, 1920\nPRICE 2 CENTS\nHere Is Your Opportunity\nto own a Summer or all-year-round HOME in the country at\nWildwood Gardens\nlocated at the Junction of the Reading and Wildwood Dela\nware Bay Short Line Railroad, directly on the new concrete\nState Road, 10 minutes by train to Wildwood, 90 minutes to\nPhiladelphia.\nHigh virgin land, fertile aoil. pure water, apple trees and old\nshade trees now growing on this property.\nSPECIAL prices for the first 100 lots. 100 to *200 each.\nOnly *10 down and *5 to *10 per month. A discount of 10\nper cent will be allowed for a short time for all cash if paid within\n30 days after date of sale.\nIMMEDIATE POSSESSION can be given to those wishing to\nplant a garden now, or to those who desire to build.\nHere is your opportunity to cut down the HIGH COST of\nLIVING. For further informaflion, inquire at farm house on prop\nerty, or\nEVANS G. SLAUGHTER. Owner. Wildwood. N. J.\nPremier Bakery\nPine and Pacific Aves. Wildwood, N. J.\nOur Own Baking\u2014Wheat and Rye Breads\nAssorted Cakes and Pies\nCustomers from Anglesea and Crest should get off at Pine Ave.\nand walk one block West. Colonial Ice Cream served by the\nplate or quart.\nHENRY HILL, Prop.\nElectric\nPortables\nat prices that beat Phila\ndelphia prices. See our\ndisplay and make your\nselection now.\nAlso see the Free West\ninghouse Sewing Machine\nwith motor attached and\nnote OUR price. Then\nwe have the \u201cE Z\u2019\u2019 motor\ncomplete and ready for\nattaching to any sewing\nmachine.\nElectrical devices will do\nmuch to help YOU.\nWEST JERSEY\nELECTRIC CO.\nSheriff\u2019s Sale\nOF\nValuable Real Estate\nHouse and lot situate in the busi\nness section of Wildwood and\nknown as No. 4209 Pacific Ave.,\nwill be sold on\nMonday, June 14th, 1920\nat one o'clock in the afternoon\nat the Sheriff\u2019s office at Cape\nMay Court House, to the\nhighest bidder.\nDR. CHAS. A. FUREY\nPOST GRADUATE OSTEOPATH\n220 East Wildwood Avenue Both Phones\nPhiladelphia office. Real Eatate Trust building\nPhone Walnut 1598.\nCape May office 124 Decatur street\nKeystone Phone\nWhich Way Are The \u201cTrade Winds\u201d Really Blowing\nIt is high time that a certain type of American busi\nness men cease worrying, and take comfort fr<5m some\nplain, easily-discoverable facts.\nI sense a tendency on the part of a few business men\nhere and there to construe present unusual commercial\nconditions as the inevitable forerunner of panic condi\ntions.\nAlso, I can put my finger on what I consider a very\nstupid inclination among certain thoughtless persons to\nshrug their shoulders at any mild suggestion that the\nbusiness of this country is not necessarily going to blow\nup with a loud and resonant crash within the next\neighteen mouths!\nIf one has the interest to chase this pessimism to its\nsource, then puts that source under the magnifying glass\nof intelligent, uninflamed business analysis, of what does\nhe find it to consist?\nJust this Commodities are very high the consuming\npublic is crying more nearly in nnison every day for\nlower prices labor is in an aggravated etate of unrest;\nand commercial, social and political conditions in Europe\nare generally bad.\nGranted\u2014every bit of it!\nBut, even so, bear with us while we decline to become\nfrenzied over these thiugs, and allow us for a moment to\nput the facts through a'laboratory test.\nWhich way are the trade wiuds really blowing?\nSo far as I know, or can find out, no business depres\nsion in the United States ever occurred in or immediately\nfollowed a period in which money was anywhere nearly\nas plentiful as it is today and has been for two years\u2014\nwith a record-breaking gold balauce to justify and even\nnecessitate it.\nSo far as I know, no commercial cataclysm in this\ncountry of ours has ever come at a time of conspicuous\nunder-production of necessities.\nAnd so far as I know, or can find out, no real business\nparalysis has ever accompanied or immediately suc\nceeded a time when the workingman\u2014or the farmeiv\nwas anywhere nearly so much the master of his financial\ndestiny as he admittedly is today.\nTruly, I think the well-known volatile temper of the\nAmerican business man has never been more strikingly\ndemonstrated than in this silly inclination on the part\nof a few of him to mistake the probably approaching\nreadjustment of commercial matters for a stagnation.\nAnd here, I think, we get the real answer We shall\nhave a clarifying of industrial relations, a slraiqhtening-out\nof commodity values, and perhaps of trading prices and\nprofits ratios\u2014but a panic, a business depression, a period\nof radical commercial curtailment, NO I\nWhat I am principally quarreling with is the super\nficial characier of the judgment that a few self-appointed\ncalamity-bowlers always insist on applying to a business\nsituation whenever it is anything but 100 per cent rosy.\nThey like to interpret a prospective, natural easing-off\nof abnormally high prices as a bottom-dropped-out affair.\nThey view an upset labor situation as forecasting an\nindustrial tragedy\u2014entirely forgetting, apparently, that\na labor crisis never comes when production of living ne\ncessities is tremendously under normal requirements.\nTo them the unparalleled accumulation of gold reserves\nin this country at present, with its unavoidable influence\ntoward high prices, high wages aud popular extrava\ngance, means nothing at all!\nTwo years ago everyone was proclaiming, truthfully,\nthat business in the United Siates is just entering an\nera of the greatest prosperity it has ever known.\u201d\nRight!\u2014and we ARE in it, and, if we will merely ignore or\nsuppress the stupid croakers, we shall easily continue in pros\nperity for many years I\nIf I should epitomize the worth-while statements made\nto me of late by the worth-while men of business, they\nwould come down to about this\nLet\u2019s not even dream of poor business while all\nabout us we have, and must for a long time have,\nelements that make business secure.\u201d\nThose who are the real thinkers can see business in the\nUnited States on no.hing but a solid foundation\u2014made\nso by piactically every economic factor required for com\nmercial security.\nYes, prices are going to be revised dowuward, some\ntime; broadcast personal extravagance is going to run\nits course, and prosperous sanity return labor is going\nto rub its eyes clear and jump enthusiastically into the\npleasant and profiiable work o( making production more\nnearly match the demand for it.\nWho are goiDg to straighten out the situation, and\nbring America\u2019s business to its proper basis without inter\nrupting it?\nThe Americah people themselves\u2014of course\nThey have always been able to get about anything on\nearth that they wanted. They are always the final con\ntrolling factor in our business life, if they wish to be.\nThey don\u2019t want business depression.\nTherefore, we are not going to have it.\nReprinted From \u201cHardware Age\u2019\u2019 for the\nJ. H. Coombs Lumber Co., Inc.\nLINCOLN, SCHELLENGER and HOLLY BEACH AVENUES\nCity Hall Doings\n\u201cThere\u2019s no price set on the lavish\nsummer;\nJune may be had by the poorest\ncomer.\u201d\n\u201cAnd what is so rare as a day in June?\nThen, if ever, come perfect days\nThen heaven tries the earth if it be\nin tune,\nAnd over it softly her warm ear\nlavs.\u201d\nLast Tuesday, June 8th, was one of\nthese ideal days about which James\nRa|seil Lowell raved so deliciously in\nhis<\u2018Vision of Sir Launfal,\u201d and some\nthing ofthe poet\u2019s spirit must have en\ntered the minds of those persons\u2014in\ncluding a goodly number of the fair\nones\u2014who wended their way on that\nperfect day to city, hall to be present at\nthe regular weekly meeting of the Com\nmissioners. Wistful eyes, ever and\nanon, were cast upon the wall where\nhung the friendly city clock\u2014only to\nbe rewarded by being \u201cbent on va\ncancy.\u201d No word of encouragement\ncame from the city clerks as to what\nprogress is being made with the petro\nleum treatment previously recommend\ned. It is to be hoped that our city\ntimekeeper will soon have its joints\nsufficiently lubricated to be able to re\nsume its duties once again on the same\nold epot.\nOwing to the tardiness of Commis\nsioner Smith, it was nearly 1 45 p. m.\nwhen the meeting was called to order.\nFrom May 25th to Juue 5th, inclu\nsive, the tax receipts were reported to\nhave been $41,568.69, and the receipts\nin the water department, $927 46.\nIn the past week water was turned\non in fourteen places for arriving con\nsumers. Three additional tape made\nto the mains of our water supply sys\ntem were as follows: At 110 east Seven\nteenth street, for Mr. Webster; on\nEighteenth street east of Ocean avenue,\nfor H. H. Otteps, and on Second ave\nnue west of Central avenue, for A. M.\nEly.\nDuring the month of May the city\ntax collector reported that twenty-six\nsearches had been made for diHerent\npersons and that the sums collected in\nfees for this service amounted to $53.50.\nA communication from Dr. Cohen\nwas next read, tendering bis resigna\ntion as health officer and registrar of\nvital statistics. This was received and\nfiled. The Mayor announced that the\nappointment of his successor would be\nheld over until next week.\nThe following communication from\nFrank L. King was now read \u201cI here\nby tender my services for the position\nof real estate assessor, being made va\ncant by the resignation of the present\nincumbent. Having been in the real\nestate business for the past ten years in\nWildwood, I feel qualified to till the\nposition with credit and honor to the\nCity of Wildwood and its taxpayers.\u201d\nA second commuication from Frank L.\nKing was read oflering to the city any\nnumber of benches, ranging in length\nfrom 10 feet to 16 feet, at the price of\n121 cents per lineal foot, including the\ncleats and galvanized nails for securing\nbenches to board walk. These benches\nwere formerly the property of the U.\n8. Government at Cape May. Consid\neration of this proposition was referred\nto the commissioner of streets.\nThe Mayor let It be known that the\ncity is iu need of two more life boats;\nalso of a pair of horses to be used in the\nremoval of garbage. It is rumored\nthat the Mayor has since purchased a\npair of horses from Sherman T. Dowler\nfor the sum of $300.\nThe issuance of an emergency note\nwas authorized to meet current ex\npeases.'\nA contract amounting to $120 was\nawarded Frank E. Grapewine to paper\nall the second floor rooms and bails of\nour municipal building. Mr. Grape\nwine, it appears, was the only bidder.\nFrank L. King, who was present at\nthe meeting, boasted that he was a\nmuch licensed man. He paid five\nlicense fees, as follows: \u201cMercantile\nlicense, real estate or broker\u2019s license,\nauctioneer\u2019s license, two dog licenses\nand a poll tax or voting license.\u201d In\nregard to the poll tax he is In error.\nIn Pennsylvania a poll tax Is equiva\nlent to a license fee for the privilege of\nvoting, but not so in Jersey.\nEdivard E. Rhoads was an interested\nspectator ai.d also an actor at one stage\nof the proceedings, when he arose to\nprotest against the heavy increase in\nhis assessments and taxes this year\nover those of 1919. Last year his\ntaxes were $998, this year $4,015.67.\nLast year the assessments on his\nground and buildings amounted to\n$52,500, this year the assessments were\nincreased $43,500, making a total of\n$96,000. Commissioner Smith made a\nmotion that the County Tax Board be\nrequested to reduce Mr. Rhoads\u2019 assess\nment to the extent of $20,000.\nThe Officers and\nDirectors of the\nMarine National\nBank extend\ntheir greetings\nto Summer Sea\nshore Visitors\nand invite them,\nto call at this\nBank when in\nneed of any financial service. We are confident, if you\navail yourself of our service, you will find it much more\nconvenient than through some out of town bank. We\nwould appreciate an opportunity to demonstrate our\nservice.\nThe Marine National Bank\nWildwood and Pacific Aves. Wildwood, N. J.\nMembers of the Federal Reserve Banking System\nTo Our Summer\nSeashore Visitor:\nGreeting\nDR. WILLIAM ZIESEL\nDENTIST\nRe\"'ov*d Mls Magnolia Avenue and Boardwalk to Wildwood Title Trust Co.,\nOffices Prom cor. M^i/dMrood and Af/anfic Aves., M^ilcfsirood, M. 7. Both Phones\nDr. Josephine Belle cZ\u00b0PsRP^\u00a3R\nWednesdays and Saturdays\nCorner Wildwood and Atlantic Aves. Wildwood, N. J.\nDD. S. E. CORLE\nDENTIST\nUNION BANK BUILDING\nXRAY SERVICE BOTH PHONES\nI\nMelchiorre, Genuine Economist\n3312-14 Pacific Avenue Under Seacrest Hofei\nThe Store of Personal Service\nRegal Shoes\n20%, Five Day Reduction Sale now going on. Sale closes\nSaturday Night, June 12, at Eleven o\u2019clock.\n\n1\nLydia J. Meech, president of the\nWildwood Civic club, accompanied by\nthe ex-Secretary, Mrs. Kathryn Don\naghy, called on the commissioners on\nTuesday to ascertain what progress\nwas being made toward providing a\npublic rest room for women in the\nvicinity of Magnolia avenue and board\nwalk. To the dismay of everybody\npresent, the Mayor stated that on ac\ncount of the scarcity of material and\nlabor it would be impossible to build\nthe proposed new\u2019 structure this sea\nson, and for which purpose the sum of\n$6,200 was appropriated. The lease of\nsome suitable building or rooms for the\npresent season may be a temporary\nsolution of the problem. Next year\nbuilding conditions may be different.\nLast season the Civic club had charge\nof a room on the boardwalk in the\nvicinity of Juniper avenue.\nMrs. C. W. Wagner, owner of the\nGarfield hotel, and the Mieses Helen\nand Kathryn Kerrigan, owners of the\nBleuheim-Cheviot apartments on east\nGarfield avenue, remonstrated with\nthe commissioners about the baseball\npark and fence obstructing the ocean\nview at the foot of Garfield avenue,\nand asking for its removal from the\nbeach altogether, or at least to a point\nfarther down. The park was spoken\nof as \"an eyesore aud a disgrace to\nWildwood,\u201d aud the boards around\nthe grounds as \"a hideous and unsight\nly back-yard fence.\u201d\nCommissioner Smith stated at Tues\nday\u2019s meeting that John Harris, of\nCamden, would be preseut at the com\nmissioners\u2019 meeting next Tuesday,\nJune loth, at which time, he averred a\nwrit from the Court of Chancery would\nbe served on the city\u2019s representatives,\nordering the tearing up and removal of\nthe present boardwalk from Schellen\nger to Cresse avenues. This informa\ntion seemed to frighten some of the\npeople and Commissioner Bright said:\n\"Let us do something before the writ\nis served.\u201d Thereupon he immediate\nly moved that the sale of the $50,000\nbond issue be proceeded with at once.\nCommissioner Smith heartily seconded\nthe motion and it was rushed through\nby a two to one vote, Mayor Hendee\nvoting no loudly with all his might.\nHe wanted it to be known that this is\nnot the time to oiler five per cent bonds\nfor sale. He feared they may go a beg\nging. This is the sequel to the Culver\nand Mowitz suits, judgment has been\ngranted by default as former Mayor\nSmith and former Commissioner Ryan\nlaid down and refused to put up a\ndefense.\n--HO*\nWe have just received a line of\nO\u2019Shaughuesey books, fishing rods,\nsinkers and lines at Empol\u2019a.\u2014\nFOR SALE\nSteams Knight 1918 8 cylinder\n7 passenger touring car\nGood rubber all around. A-l\ncondition. Good for hacking or\nhotel use. For full particulars call\nim Pacific Aye., Beers\u2019 f?gf\u00a3\nTfoeo. Foote, n. D.d\nOFFICE and RESIDENCE\n5800 Pacific Ave., Cor. Heather Road\nOffice Hours: Until 9 a. m., 1 to 3 6 to 7 p. m.\nOffice Hours ou Fridays t> to 7 p. m. only\nKilmer Carll\nPractical House Movers\nand Contractors\nEstimates Cheerfully Given\nWILDWOOD NEW JEHSEY","height":"26064","width":"18416"}}
